both the assertion and the refashioning of individual and communal identity in transcultural contexts. Three shared assumptions guide these essays: religion plays a dynamic role in the shaping and reshaping of social cultures; women are active participants in their transmission and their transformation; and a focus on women's activities within their religious traditions—often informal and unofficial—provides new perspectives on the intersection of religion, gender, and transnationalism. Since the first European migrations, Canada has been shaped by immigrant communities as they negotiated the tension between preserving their religious and cultural traditions and embracing the new opportunities in their adopted homeland. Viewing those interactions through the lens of women’s religiosity, the essays in this collection model an innovative approach and provide new perspectives for students and researchers of Canadian Studies, Religious Studies, and Women’s Studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminismzCanadaxReligious aspects. 0aWomenxReligious lifezCanada. 4aReligion. 4aReligion: Spirituality. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh  aTransnational.  achildbirth.  agender.  ahybridity.  aimmigrants.  amulticulturalism.  asocial action.  atranscultural.1 aBowman, Marion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEchevarria, Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldberg, Aviva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Becky R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLee, Decky B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMccann, Gillian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMor